text: Brood X is the largest and most widespread group of periodical cicadas in the United States. But with 15 periodical broods that emerge in predictable cycles of every 13 or 17 years, a massive cicada emergence can be found in some part of the country just about every year https://t.co/8Pd7WD2VXE
name: TIME

text:
Six to 10 weeks later, the eggs hatch into tiny nymphs, which fall to the earth and tunnel underground. 

The nymphs spend the next 17 years sucking on plant sap, waiting for their big moment back in the sun https://t.co/jphDDG4Rw1
name: TIME
description: News and current events from around the globe. Subscribe: https://t.co/yT0dueLEm0

text:
After male and female cicadas hook up, the females slice into small tree branches using their ovipositor—a saw-like organ—and lay nests of 20 to 30 eggs at a time. 

Females may lay 400 to 600 eggs in total before tumbling to the ground and dying https://t.co/fKP8UQ74Du
name: TIME
description: News and current events from around the globe. Subscribe: https://t.co/yT0dueLEm0

text: Birds, snakes, turtles, spiders, and small mammals love to eat cicadas—yet all this predation will barely put a dent in their population https://t.co/ATX0Wxy0qk
name: TIME
description: News and current events from around the globe. Subscribe: https://t.co/yT0dueLEm0

text:
To woo females, male cicadas emit an ear-splitting mating call—muscle contractions cause their tymbal organ to vibrate, and their hollow abdomen amplifies the sound to deafening levels. 

A chorus of cicadas can reach 80 to 100 decibels—as loud as a lawnmower https://t.co/LxPmFV5vJe
name: TIME
description: News and current events from around the globe. Subscribe: https://t.co/yT0dueLEm0
